        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>
In setup 1, we will observe three lines, C18O(3-2), 13CO(3-2), CS(7-6), and the Band 7 continuum. For the lines, we selected a spectral resolution of 0.05 km/s, in order to resolve the 3 km/s wide line into about 60 resolution elements. This will ensure that we can adequately study the line profile and analyze the different broadening effects, such as turbulence.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>
Although our target has never been resolved at (sub)millimeter wavelengths, we expect that its diameter does not exceed 2 arcsec (310 au at a distance of 155 pc). For such source, the finest resolution where we do not loose significant flux due to the filtering of large-scale emission is 0.15 arcsec in Band 7. Using our APEX line fluxes and our radiative transfer model, we simulated the disk image and run simobserve in CASA with the C36-5 configuration to verify that there is enough flux in such small beams for most of the disk area. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>
We based our sensitivity calculations on our radiative transfer model of the disk of EX Lup. We calculated 12CO, 13CO, and C18O line fluxes both for the J=3-2 transition (in Band 7) and for the J=2-1 transition (in Band 6). Our simulations suggest that the 3-2 lines are so much brighter in our target that they can be detected in less time than the 2-1 lines would be in Band 6. Thus, we will go for Band 7 observations.

In this setup, our sensitivity calculations are driven by the 13CO line, where we measured a total flux of 2.1 Jy.km/s with APEX (we note that this is a marginal detection, but our model simulations support this value). Considering the number of beams and spectral resolution elements into which the source flux will be distributed, and the fact that we want to detect the signal at least at a 5 sigma level, we request a sensitivity of 10 mJy per beam per resolution element. According to the ALMA sensitivity calculator, this can be accomplished in 1.02 h.

Together in the two science goals, we have three TDM windows for the continuum, yielding a total of 6 GHz aggregate bandwidth. According to the ALMA sensitivity calculator, this will result in a continuum sensitivity of 0.030 mJy, ensuring the detection of the continuum emission with a high signal to noise ratio (the total continuum flux of our target is 41 mJy).</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>
The 12m array data rate exceeds the policy value, but this is unavoidable, because we need the observe three different lines with good spectral resolution in order to adequately resolve the line profiles.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_HIGH_DATA_RATE</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
    </prj:ScienceGoal>
