    <prp:abstract>A fundamental physical process in the formation of Sun-like stars is the transportation of material from the circumstellar disk onto the star. This transport can be studied with exceptional clarity in young eruptive stars. Investigating a large outburst of EX Lup, a prototype of young eruptive stars, we have learnt many aspects of both the inward and the outward transportation of matter in the system. Based on those results, we are now developing a general transport model for EX Lup, involving a global 3-dimensional MHD code. However, many fundamental inputs to this transport model are still missing, and can only be provided by ALMA. Based on detailed chemical and radiative transfer simulations of the disk, we propose to obtain 880 micrometer dust continuum and J=3-2
line maps of 12CO, 13CO, and C18O with ALMA. We will determine the basic parameters of the gas and dust disk and the star, and investigate the turbulence and viscosity in the outer disk. The general transport model will be a large step forward to obtain a coherent picture of the accretion process in a prototypical young eruptive star, and, in general, in
low-mass T Tauri stars.</prp:abstract>
